re, Bentons in Suffolk, and Little Benton and Longbenton in Northumberland. The places are named with Old English <i>bēan</i> ‘beans’ (a collective singular) or <i>beonet</i> ‘bent grass’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘enclosure, settlement’.","in Yorkshire and possibly also Staffordshire, a variant of   Bentham  .","English:"],"variants":[{"name":"Bentham","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of various places so named, but primarily from Bentham in Yorkshire or Gloucestershire; named from Old English <i>beonet</i> ‘bent grass’ + <i>hām</i> ‘homestead, estate’ or <i>hamm</i> ‘enclosure hemmed in by water’."]}]},{"name":"Anne","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Pet form of   Ann   or   Anne ."],"variants":[{"name":"Anni","meanings":["Pet form of   Ann   or   Anne ."]}]},{"name":"Matilda","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized form of a Germanic personal name derived from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’. This was the name of an early German queen (  895–968 ), wife of  Henry  the Fowler, who was noted for her piety and generosity. It was also the name of the wife of  William  the Conqueror and of the daughter of  Henry I  of England (  see  Maud  ). The name was introduced into England by the Normans, and this Latinized form is the one that normally occurs in medieval records, while the vernacular form <i>Maud</i> was the one in everyday use. <i>Matilda</i> was revived in England as a learned form in the 18th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Mathilda","meanings":["Latinized form of a Germanic personal name derived from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’. This was the name of an early German queen (  895–968 ), wife of  Henry  the Fowler, who was noted for her piety and generosity. It was also the name of the wife of  William  the Conqueror and of the daughter of  Henry I  of England (  see  Maud  ). The name was introduced into England by the Normans, and this Latinized form is the one that normally occurs in medieval records, while the vernacular form <i>Maud</i> was the one in everyday use. <i>Matilda</i> was revived in England as a learned form in the 18th century."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Anne Matilda Benton was born on 12 December 1407, in Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom. She married Thomas Freebody in 1430, in Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died on 23 September 1485, in Islington, London, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 77."},"et":{"12 Dec 1407–23 Sep 1485":"12. detsember 1407–23. september 1485","1404–1437":"1404–1437","1433–1491":"1433–1491","1407–1485":"1407–1485","1437":"1437","1404":"1404","1433":"1433","24 September 1433":"24. september 1433","1430":"1430","1485":"1485","23 Sep 1485":"23. september 1485","12 Dec 1407":"12. detsember 1407","1491":"1491","1407":"1407","06 Nov 1437":"6. november 1437","Islington, London, England":"Islington, London, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Stepney, Middlesex, England":"Stepney, Middlesex, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"12 Dec 1407–23 Sep 1485":"12. joulukuuta 1407–23. syyskuuta 1485","1404–1437":"1404–1437","1433–1491":"1433–1491","1407–1485":"1407–1485","1437":"1437","1404":"1404","1433":"1433","24 September 1433":"24. syyskuuta 1433","1430":"1430","1485":"1485","23 Sep 1485":"23. syyskuuta 1485","12 Dec 1407":"12. joulukuuta 1407","1491":"1491","1407":"1407","06 Nov 1437":"6. marraskuuta 1437","Islington, London, England":"Islington, London, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Stepney, Middlesex, England":"Stepney, Middlesex, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"12 Dec 1407–23 Sep 1485":"12 décembre 1407–23 septembre 1485","1404–1437":"1404–1437","1433–1